Upon these declarations and promises 116 was placed in the Pro- fessorship.

On first entering upon his Professorship he seemed to take much pains to remove from himself all suspicion of heterodoxy, by publicly maintaining theses in favour of the received doctrines 3—doctrines which he afterwards zealously contradicted. And that he did this contrary to to his own conviction at the time, was made abundantly evident afterwards by some of his own zealous friends. But after he had been in his new office a year or two, it was discovered that it was his constant practice to deliver one set of opinions in his professorial chair‚ and a very different set by means of private confidential manuscripts circulated among his pupils* He was also accustomcd, while he publicly recommended the characters and opin- ions of the most illustrious Reformed divines, artfully to insinuate such things as were adapted, indirectly‚ to bring them into discredit, and to weaken the arguments usually - brought for their support. He also frequently intimated to his pupils, that he had many objections to the doctrines usually deemed orthodox‚ which he intended to make known at a suitable time.
